 Wexford County, Michigan]]\n[[Category:Unincorporated communities in Michigan]]\n[[Category:Census-designated places in Wexford County, Michigan]]\n[[Category:Census-designated places in Michigan]]\n\n\n{{WexfordCountyMI-geo-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Notorious4life", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Haring,_Michigan"}
{"title_page": "Joe Harper", "text_new": "{{other people|Joseph Harper}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2012}}\n{{Use British English|date=March 2012}}\n{{infobox football biography\n| name     = Joe Harper\n| image          = \n| fullname       = Joseph Montgomery Harper<ref>[http://www.londonhearts.com/scotland/players/josephmontgomeryharper.html Joseph Harper], London Hearts.</ref>\n| birth_date    = {{birth date and age|1948|1|11|df=y}}\n| birth_place = [[Greenock]], Scotland\n| height = {{height|m=1.68}}<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.worldfootball.net/spieler_profil/joe-harper/|title=Joe Harper|publisher=}}</ref>\n| position       = [[Striker (association football)|Striker]]\n| youthyears1 = | youthclubs1 = \n| years1 = 1963\u20131967 | caps1 = 45  | goals1 = 36 | clubs1 = [[Greenock Morton F.C.|Morton]]\n| years2 = 1967\u20131968 | caps2 = 28  | goals2 = 4  | clubs2 = [[Huddersfield Town A.F.C.|Huddersfield Town]]\n| years3 = 1968\u20131969 | caps3 = 40  | goals3 = 29 | clubs3 = [[Greenock Morton F.C.|Morton]]\n| years4 = 1969\u20131972 | caps4 = 102 | goals4 = 68 | clubs4 = [[Aberdeen F.C.|Aberdeen]]\n| years5 = 1972\u20131974 | caps5 = 43  | goals5 = 12 | clubs5 = [[Everton F.C.|Everton]]\n| years6 = 1974\u20131976 | caps6 = 69  | goals6 = 26 | clubs6 = [[Hibernian F.C.|Hibernian]]\n| years7 = 1976\u20131981 | caps7 = 105 | goals7 = 57 | clubs7 = [[Aberdeen F.C.|Aberdeen]]\n| years8 = 1981\u20131982 | caps8 =     | goals8 =    | clubs8 = [[Peterhead F.C.|Peterhead]]\n| years9 = 1982\u20131984 | caps9 =     | goals9 =    | clubs9 = [[Keith F.C.|Keith]]\n| totalcaps = 432 | totalgoals = 232\n| nationalyears1 = 1969      | nationalteam1  = [[Scottish League XI]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.londonhearts.com/SFL/players/joeharper.html|title=Joe Harper - Scotland Football League Record from 05 Sep 1969  to  05 Sep 1969  clubs -  Aberdeen|publisher=}}</ref>\n| nationalcaps1  = 1         | nationalgoals1 = 2\n| nationalyears2 = 1972\u20131978 | nationalteam2  = [[Scotland national football team|Scotland]]\n| nationalcaps2  = 4         | nationalgoals2 = 2\n| manageryears1  = 1981\u20131982 | managerclubs1 = [[Peterhead F.C.|Peterhead]]\n| manageryears2  = \u20131990 | managerclubs2 = [[Huntly F.C.|Huntly]]\n\n}}\n'''Joseph Montgomery Harper''' (born 11 January 1948) is a Scottish former [[Association football|footballer]], mainly remembered for his two spells with [[Aberdeen F.C.|Aberdeen]], during which he won the three main domestic trophies once each and became [[List of Aberdeen F.C. records and statistics|the club's record goalscorer]] with 199 goals in major competitions. He also played for [[Greenock Morton F.C.|Morton]] (two spells) and [[Hibernian F.C.|Hibernian]] in Scotland, and for [[Huddersfield Town A.F.C.|Huddersfield Town]] and in England. He finished his career in the [[Highland Football League|Highland League]].\n\nHarper played for the [[Scotland national football team|Scotland national team]] four times, scoring twice. \n\n==Club career==\nBorn in [[Greenock]], Harper started his professional career with home-town club [[Greenock Morton F.C.|Morton]], and returned to the club after a brief, unhappy spell with [[Huddersfield Town A.F.C.|Huddersfield Town]]. He had at times a difficult relationship with some Morton supporters, but most fans recognised his ability and enthusiasm. He played for Morton against [[Chelsea F.C.|Chelsea]] in the [[Inter-Cities Fairs Cup|Fairs Cup]].<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.greenocktelegraph.co.uk/news/18003290.ton-legend-joe-harpertakes-place-among-football-greats-scottish-football-hall-fame/ | title=Ex Morton man Joe Harper enters Scottish Football Hall of Fame | publisher=[[Greenock Telegraph]] | date=1 November 2019 | accessdate=6 April 2020}}</ref> Harper scored 74 goals in 122 appearances for Morton across both spells. Morton sold him for \u00a335,000 to Huddersfield Town. He later returned to Morton for \u00a315,000.<ref>{{cite web | url=https://gmfc.net/2018/10/24/little-joe-receives-big-welcome-on-homecoming/ | title='LITTLE JOE\u2019 RECEIVES BIG WELCOME ON HOMECOMING | publisher=GMFC.net | date=24 October 2018 | accessdate=6 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nIn 1969, Aberdeen manager [[Eddie Turnbull]] paid \u00a340,000 to sign Harper, and in his first season with the ''Dons'' he helped them win the [[Scottish Cup]] for the second time in their history; Harper opened the scoring from the penalty spot as overwhelming pre-match favourites [[Celtic F.C.|Celtic]] were defeated 3\u20131. He rapidly developed a reputation as a prodigious goalscorer and following a record-breaking haul of 33 goals in 34 league games in the [[1971-72 in Scottish football|1971\u201372 season]] was the subject of much interest from English scouts.\n\n[[Everton F.C.|Everton]] paid \u00a3180,000 for his services in December 1972 but his time in English football was not as productive as his Aberdeen spell and he returned to Scotland with [[Hibernian F.C.|Hibernian]] in early 1974, for the second time signed by Eddie Turnbull who had by this stage moved to [[Easter Road]]. Overweight and unfit when he arrived at Hibs, Harper struggled to rediscover his Aberdeen-era form in [[Edinburgh]]. He scored a hat-trick in the [[1974 Scottish League Cup Final]], but [[Dixie Deans]] also scored a hat-trick as Celtic defeated Hibs 6\u20133.<ref name=elite>{{cite news|url=http://www.scotsman.com/sport/football/the-elite-players-who-scored-cup-final-hat-tricks-1-3589574|title=The elite players who scored cup final hat-tricks|newspaper=The Scotsman|date=31 October 2014|accessdate=27 November 2017}}</ref> Harper was never a favourite with the Hibs fans, and his arrival signalled the beginning of the decline of the team's fortunes through the late 1970s and 1980s.\n\nHarper returned to Aberdeen under [[Ally MacLeod]] for the start of the [[1976-77 in Scottish football|1976\u201377 season]] in a \u00a350,000 deal and inspired instant success, the ''Dons'' defeating Celtic 2\u20131 (after [[extra time]]) to win the League Cup in November. Harper made further final appearances in each of the next two seasons, as Aberdeen lost both the [[1977-78 in Scottish football|1977\u201378]] Scottish Cup final and the [[1978-79 in Scottish football|1978\u201379]] League Cup final to [[Rangers F.C.|Rangers]], by a scoreline of 2\u20131 on each occasion. By the [[1979-80 in Scottish football|1979\u201380 season]] he was considered a veteran and no longer a regular in the ''Dons'' first team but his seven goals helped [[Alex Ferguson]] become the second Scottish League-winning Aberdeen manager after [[Dave Halliday]] in [[1954-55 in Scottish football|1954\u201355]].<ref name=dh>[http://qosfc.com/legend-1048 \"Dave Halliday\" qosfc.com]</ref> Harper left Pittodrie after only one appearance the following season.\n\nIn total Harper scored 205 competitive goals for Aberdeen, a club record. Of that total, 122 were scored in league fixtures, 70 in domestic cup games (including 6 in the pre-season [[Drybrough Cup]], not counted in some totals) and 7 in European competition. His iconic status amongst Aberdeen supporters was recognised when he was amongst the first players to be inducted to the club's \"Hall of Fame\". Joe's notoriety with Aberdeen fans also earned him the title 'King of the Beach End' (traditional home end at Pittodrie).\n\n==International career==\nHarper first played for [[Scotland national football team|Scotland]] against [[Denmark national football team|Denmark]] in October 1972, scoring on his debut in a 4\u20131 win.<ref name = \"ordinary\">{{cite news |url=http://www.scotsman.com/sport/joe-harper-interview-no-ordinary-joe-1-1301602 |title=Joe Harper interview: No ordinary Joe |work=The Scotsman |publisher= |date=22 November 2008 |accessdate=29 April 2016}}</ref> He played in Scotland's next game but then fell out of the international reckoning, only earning a recall in 1975. By coincidence, the occasion was another away match with Denmark, but this was overshadowed by a controversial off-field incident. Harper and several teammates were given lifetime bans by the [[Scottish Football Association]] after it was alleged that they had been involved in a nightclub incident where a light was broken and an altercation followed.<ref name = \"copenhagen\">{{cite web |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/internationals/7977173.stm |title=Scotland's hall of shame |work=BBC Sport |publisher= BBC |date=1 April 2009 |accessdate=26 August 2013}}</ref> Harper later said that he had been punished because he had returned to the team base in the same taxi as the other players.<ref name = \"copenhagen\"/> The ban on two of the players, Harper and [[Arthur Graham]], was lifted a year later.<ref name = \"copenhagen\"/> Harper was selected in the Scotland squad for the [[1978 FIFA World Cup]]. He appeared in the 1\u20131 draw against [[Iran national football team|Iran]], which was also his last international appearance, as Scotland exited in the first round.<ref name = \"ordinary\"/>\n\n==Later life==\nIn 1981 Harper was appointed manager of then [[Highland Football League|Highland League]] side [[Peterhead F.C.|Peterhead]]. He helped the ''Blue Toon'' to a second place league finish but his reported wages were beyond the club's means and he was replaced for the 1982\u201383 season by former Pittodrie teammate Dave Smith.<ref>[http://www.peterheadfc.org.uk/history/part6.shtml Peterhead Club History] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070808185804/http://www.peterheadfc.org.uk/history/part6.shtml |date=8 August 2007 }}, Official [[Peterhead F.C.|Peterhead]] website.</ref> Harper later managed [[Huntly F.C.|Huntly]], where he was succeeded by [[Steve Paterson]] in October 1990.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2002/dec/11/newsstory.sport6 |title=Who is Steve Paterson? |work=The Guardian |publisher= |date=11 December 2002 |accessdate=27 October 2015}}</ref>\n\nHarper has also been a columnist for the ''[[Evening Express (Scotland)|Aberdeen Evening Express]]''. An autobiography, which was co-written by ''Evening Express'' sports editor [[Charlie Allan (journalist)|Charlie Allan]], was published in 2008.<ref name = \"ordinary\"/> Harper was appointed honorary Club President of Aberdeenshire Amateur League side [[Halliburton AFC]] in 2009. He can usually be found on home match days for Aberdeen in as the host of the Legends Hospitality Lounge of the Richard Donald stand at [[Pittodrie Stadium]].\n\n==Career statistics==\n===International appearances===\n\n{| class=wikitable style=\"text-align:center\"\n|+ Appearances and goals by national team and year<ref name = \"SFA\">{{SFA Profile|id=13586}}</ref>\n|-\n!National team!!Year!!Apps!!Goals\n|-\n|rowspan=\"3\"|[[Scotland national football team|Scotland]]\n|1972||2||1\n|-\n|1975||1||1\n|-\n|1978||1||0\n|-\n!colspan=\"2\"|Total!!4!!2\n|}\n\n===International goals===\n\n:''Scores and results list Scotland's goal tally first''\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n! No. !! Date !! Venue !! Opponent !! Score !! Result !! Competition !! Ref\n|-\n| align=center | 1. || 18 October 1972 || [[Idraetsparken]], [[Copenhagen]] || {{fb|Denmark}} || align=center | 3\u20131 || align=center | 4\u20131 || [[1974 FIFA World Cup qualification]] || <ref name = \"SFA\"/><ref name = \"RSSSF 1970\">{{cite web |url=http://www.rsssf.com/tabless/scot-intres1975.html |title=Scotland - International Matches 1971-1975 |website= |publisher=RSSSF |date=17 October 2019 |accessdate=21 February 2020 |first1=Alan |last1=Brown |first2=Gabriele |last2=Tossani}}</ref>\n|-\n| align=center| 2. || 3 September 1975 || [[Idraetsparken]], [[Copenhagen]] || {{fb|Denmark}} || align=center | 1\u20130 || align=center | 1\u20130 || [[UEFA Euro 1976 qualifying]] || <ref name = \"SFA\"/><ref name = \"RSSSF 1970\"/>\n|-\n|}\n\n== Honours ==\n\n;Greenock Morton\n*[[List of winners of the Scottish Championship and predecessors|Scottish First Division]]: [[1966\u201367 Scottish Division Two|1966\u201367]]\n*[[Renfrewshire Cup]]: 1966\u201367<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.stmirrenprogrammes.co.uk/StMirren/STM_Match_Details.php?Season=1966&GameID=196612140 | title=14/12/1966 Renfrewshire Cup Final | publisher=SMFC Programmes | accessdate=6 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n;Aberdeen\n*[[Scottish Premier Division]]: [[1979\u201380 Scottish Premier Division|1979\u201380]]<ref name = \"dons honour\">{{cite web | url=https://www.eveningexpress.co.uk/fp/news/local/scottish-football-hall-of-fame-honour-for-dons-legend-joe-harper/ | title=Scottish Football Hall of Fame honour for Dons legend Joe Harper | publisher=[[Evening Express (Scotland)|Evening Express]] | date=2 September 2019 | accessdate=6 April 2020}}</ref>\n*[[Scottish Cup]]: [[1969\u201370 Scottish Cup|1969\u201370]]<ref name = \"dons honour\"/>\n*[[Scottish League Cup]]: [[1976\u201377 Scottish League Cup|1976\u201377]]<ref name = \"dons honour\"/>\n*[[Drybrough Cup]]: 1971\u201372<ref>[http://www.thecelticwiki.com/page/1971-08-07%3A+Aberdeen+2-1+Celtic%2C+Drybrough+Cup+Final Dandy Dons have struck it rich], Sunday Mail, 8 August 1971, via The Celtic Wiki</ref>\n*[[Aberdeenshire Cup]]: 1980\u201381<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.afcheritage.org/matches/fixtures/mreport.cfm?fixture_id=5837&season=1980-81&squad=Senior | title=AFC Match Report: Aberdeenshire Cup Final 1980/81 | publisher=AFC Heritage | accessdate=6 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n;Individual\n*[[European Golden Boot|European Bronze Boot]]: 1971\u201372<ref name = \"dons honour\"/>\n*[[Scottish Football Hall of Fame]]: 2019<ref name = \"dons honour\"/>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n;Sources\n*Harry Reid (2005), ''The Final Whistle?'', Birlinn, {{ISBN|1-84158-362-6}}\n*''King Joey'', Joe Harper with Charlie Allan, Birlinn (2008) {{ISBN|978-1-84158-767-7}}\n\n== External links ==\n*{{NeilBrownPlayers|player/joeharper}}\n*{{SFA profile}}\n\n{{Scotland Squad 1978 World Cup}}\n{{Navboxes\n| title = Awards\n| bg = gold\n| fg = \n| bordercolor = \n| list1 = \n{{Scottish First Division top scorers}}\n{{Aberdeen F.C. Hall of Fame}}\n{{Scottish Football Hall of Fame}}\n}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Harper, Joe}}\n[[Category:1948 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Scottish footballers]]\n[[Category:Aberdeen F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Everton F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Hibernian F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Greenock Morton F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Huddersfield Town A.F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Peterhead F.C. managers]]\n[[Category:Scottish football managers]]\n[[Category:Scotland international footballers]]\n[[Category:1978 FIFA World Cup players]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Greenock]]\n[[Category:Scottish Football League players]]\n[[Category:English Football League players]]\n[[Category:Association football forwards]]\n[[Category:Scottish Football League representative players]]\n[[Category:Highland Football League players]]\n[[Category:Keith F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Scotland under-23 international footballers]]\n[[Category:Scottish league football top scorers]]\n[[Category:Scottish Football Hall of Fame inductees]]\n", "text_old": "{{other people|Joseph Harper}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2012}}\n{{Use British English|date=March 2012}}\n{{infobox football biography\n| name     = Joe Harper\n| image          = \n| fullname       = Joseph Montgomery Harper<ref>[http://www.londonhearts.com/scotland/players/josephmontgomeryharper.html Joseph Harper], London Hearts.</ref>\n| birth_date    = {{birth date and age|1948|1|11|df=y}}\n| birth_place = [[Greenock]], Scotland\n| height = {{height|m=1.68}}<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.worldfootball.net/spieler_profil/joe-harper/|title=Joe Harper|publisher=}}</ref>\n| position       = [[Striker (association football)|Striker]]\n| youthyears1 = | youthclubs1 = \n| years1 = 1963\u20131967 | caps1 = 45  | goals1 = 36 | clubs1 = [[Greenock Morton F.C.|Morton]]\n| years2 = 1967\u20131968 | caps2 = 28  | goals2 = 4  | clubs2 = [[Huddersfield Town A.F.C.|Huddersfield Town]]\n| years3 = 1968\u20131969 | caps3 = 40  | goals3 = 29 | clubs3 = [[Greenock Morton F.C.|Morton]]\n| years4 = 1969\u20131972 | caps4 = 102 | goals4 = 68 | clubs4 = [[Aberdeen F.C.|Aberdeen]]\n| years5 = 1972\u20131974 | caps5 = 43  | goals5 = 12 | clubs5 = [[Everton F.C.|Everton]]\n| years6 = 1974\u20131976 | caps6 = 69  | goals6 = 26 | clubs6 = [[Hibernian F.C.|Hibernian]]\n| years7 = 1976\u20131981 | caps7 = 105 | goals7 = 57 | clubs7 = [[Aberdeen F.C.|Aberdeen]]\n| years8 = 1981\u20131982 | caps8 =     | goals8 =    | clubs8 = [[Peterhead F.C.|Peterhead]]\n| years9 = 1982\u20131984 | caps9 =     | goals9 =    | clubs9 = [[Keith F.C.|Keith]]\n| totalcaps = 432 | totalgoals = 232\n| nationalyears1 = 1969      | nationalteam1  = [[Scottish League XI]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.londonhearts.com/SFL/players/joeharper.html|title=Joe Harper - Scotland Football League Record from 05 Sep 1969  to  05 Sep 1969  clubs -  Aberdeen|publisher=}}</ref>\n| nationalcaps1  = 1         | nationalgoals1 = 2\n| nationalyears2 = 1972\u20131978 | nationalteam2  = [[Scotland national football team|Scotland]]\n| nationalcaps2  = 4         | nationalgoals2 = 2\n| manageryears1  = 1981\u20131982 | managerclubs1 = [[Peterhead F.C.|Peterhead]]\n| manageryears2  = \u20131990 | managerclubs2 = [[Huntly F.C.|Huntly]]\n\n}}\n'''Joseph Montgomery Harper''' (born 11 January 1948) is a Scottish former [[Association football|footballer]], mainly remembered for his two spells with [[Aberdeen F.C.|Aberdeen]], during which he won the three main domestic trophies once each and became [[List of Aberdeen F.C. records and statistics|the club's record goalscorer]] with 199 goals in major competitions. He also played for [[Greenock Morton F.C.|Morton]] (two spells) and [[Hibernian F.C.|Hibernian]] in Scotland, and for [[Huddersfield Town A.F.C.|Huddersfield Town]] and in England. He finished his career in the [[Highland Football League|Highland League]].\n\nHarper played for the [[Scotland national football team|Scotland national team]] four times, scoring twice. \n\n==Club career==\nBorn in [[Greenock]], Harper started his professional career with home-town club [[Greenock Morton F.C.|Morton]], and returned to the club after a brief, unhappy spell with [[Huddersfield Town A.F.C.|Huddersfield Town]]. He had at times a difficult relationship with some Morton supporters, but most fans recognised his ability and enthusiasm. He played for Morton against [[Chelsea F.C.|Chelsea]] in the [[Inter-Cities Fairs Cup|Fairs Cup]].<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.greenocktelegraph.co.uk/news/18003290.ton-legend-joe-harpertakes-place-among-football-greats-scottish-football-hall-fame/ | title=Ex Morton man Joe Harper enters Scottish Football Hall of Fame | publisher=[[Greenock Telegraph]] | date=1 November 2019 | accessdate=6 April 2020}}</ref> Harper scored 74 goals in 122 appearances for Morton across both spells. Morton sold him for \u00a335,000 to Huddersfield Town. He later returned to Morton for \u00a315,000.<ref>{{cite web | url=https://gmfc.net/2018/10/24/little-joe-receives-big-welcome-on-homecoming/ | title='LITTLE JOE\u2019 RECEIVES BIG WELCOME ON HOMECOMING | publisher=GMFC.net | date=24 October 2018 | accessdate=6 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nIn 1969, Aberdeen manager [[Eddie Turnbull]] paid \u00a340,000 to sign Harper, and in his first season with the ''Dons'' he helped them win the [[Scottish Cup]] for the second time in their history; Harper opened the scoring from the penalty spot as overwhelming pre-match favourites [[Celtic F.C.|Celtic]] were defeated 3\u20131. He rapidly developed a reputation as a prodigious goalscorer and following a record-breaking haul of 33 goals in 34 league games in the [[1971-72 in Scottish football|1971\u201372 season]] was the subject of much interest from English scouts.\n\n[[Everton F.C.|Everton]] paid \u00a3180,000 for his services in December 1972 but his time in English football was not as productive as his Aberdeen spell and he returned to Scotland with [[Hibernian F.C.|Hibernian]] in early 1974, for the second time signed by Eddie Turnbull who had by this stage moved to [[Easter Road]]. Overweight and unfit when he arrived at Hibs, Harper struggled to rediscover his Aberdeen-era form in [[Edinburgh]]. He scored a hat-trick in the [[1974 Scottish League Cup Final]], but [[Dixie Deans]] also scored a hat-trick as Celtic defeated Hibs 6\u20133.<ref name=elite>{{cite news|url=http://www.scotsman.com/sport/football/the-elite-players-who-scored-cup-final-hat-tricks-1-3589574|title=The elite players who scored cup final hat-tricks|newspaper=The Scotsman|date=31 October 2014|accessdate=27 November 2017}}</ref> Harper was never a favourite with the Hibs fans, and his arrival signalled the beginning of the decline of the team's fortunes through the late 1970s and 1980s.\n\nHarper returned to Aberdeen under [[Ally MacLeod]] for the start of the [[1976-77 in Scottish football|1976\u201377 season]] in a \u00a350,000 deal and inspired instant success, the ''Dons'' defeating Celtic 2\u20131 (after [[extra time]]) to win the League Cup in November. Harper made further final appearances in each of the next two seasons, as Aberdeen lost both the [[1977-78 in Scottish football|1977\u201378]] Scottish Cup final and the [[1978-79 in Scottish football|1978\u201379]] League Cup final to [[Rangers F.C.|Rangers]], by a scoreline of 2\u20131 on each occasion. By the [[1979-80 in Scottish football|1979\u201380 season]] he was considered a veteran and no longer a regular in the ''Dons'' first team but his seven goals helped [[Alex Ferguson]] become the second Scottish League-winning Aberdeen manager after [[Dave Halliday]] in [[1954-55 in Scottish football|1954\u201355]].<ref name=dh>[http://qosfc.com/legend-1048 \"Dave Halliday\" qosfc.com]</ref> Harper left Pittodrie after only one appearance the following season.\n\nIn total Harper scored 205 competitive goals for Aberdeen, a club record. Of that total, 122 were scored in league fixtures, 70 in domestic cup games (including 6 in the pre-season [[Drybrough Cup]], not counted in some totals) and 7 in European competition. His iconic status amongst Aberdeen supporters was recognised when he was amongst the first players to be inducted to the club's \"Hall of Fame\". Joe's notoriety with Aberdeen fans also earned him the title 'King of the Beach End' (traditional home end at Pittodrie).\n\n==International career==\nHarper first played for [[Scotland national football team|Scotland]] against [[Denmark national football team|Denmark]] in October 1972, scoring on his debut in a 4\u20131 win.<ref name = \"ordinary\">{{cite news |url=http://www.scotsman.com/sport/joe-harper-interview-no-ordinary-joe-1-1301602 |title=Joe Harper interview: No ordinary Joe |work=The Scotsman |publisher= |date=22 November 2008 |accessdate=29 April 2016}}</ref> He played in Scotland's next game but then fell out of the international reckoning, only earning a recall in 1975. By coincidence, the occasion was another away match with Denmark, but this was overshadowed by a controversial off-field incident. Harper and several teammates were given lifetime bans by the [[Scottish Football Association]] after it was alleged that they had been involved in a nightclub incident where a light was broken and an altercation followed.<ref name = \"copenhagen\">{{cite web |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/internationals/7977173.stm |title=Scotland's hall of shame |work=BBC Sport |publisher= BBC |date=1 April 2009 |accessdate=26 August 2013}}</ref> Harper later said that he had been punished because he had returned to the team base in the same taxi as the other players.<ref name = \"copenhagen\"/> The ban on two of the players, Harper and [[Arthur Graham]], was lifted a year later.<ref name = \"copenhagen\"/> Harper was selected in the Scotland squad for the [[1978 FIFA World Cup]]. He appeared in the 1\u20131 draw against [[Iran national football team|Iran]], which was also his last international appearance, as Scotland exited in the first round.<ref name = \"ordinary\"/>\n\n==Later life==\nIn 1981 Harper was appointed manager of then [[Highland Football League|Highland League]] side [[Peterhead F.C.|Peterhead]]. He helped the ''Blue Toon'' to a second place league finish but his reported wages were beyond the club's means and he was replaced for the 1982\u201383 season by former Pittodrie teammate Dave Smith.<ref>[http://www.peterheadfc.org.uk/history/part6.shtml Peterhead Club History] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070808185804/http://www.peterheadfc.org.uk/history/part6.shtml |date=8 August 2007 }}, Official [[Peterhead F.C.|Peterhead]] website.</ref> Harper later managed [[Huntly F.C.|Huntly]], where he was succeeded by [[Steve Paterson]] in October 1990.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2002/dec/11/newsstory.sport6 |title=Who is Steve Paterson? |work=The Guardian |publisher= |date=11 December 2002 |accessdate=27 October 2015}}</ref>\n\nHarper has also been a columnist for the ''[[Evening Express (Scotland)|Aberdeen Evening Express]]''. An autobiography, which was co-written by ''Evening Express'' sports editor [[Charlie Allan (journalist)|Charlie Allan]], was published in 2008.<ref name = \"ordinary\"/> Harper was appointed honorary Club President of Aberdeenshire Amateur League side [[Halliburton AFC]] in 2009. He can usually be found on home match days for Aberdeen in as the host of the Legends Hospitality Lounge of the Richard Donald stand at [[Pittodrie Stadium]].\n\n==Career statistics==\n===International appearances===\n\n{| class=wikitable style=\"text-align:center\"\n|+ Appearances and goals by national team and year<ref name = \"SFA\">{{SFA Profile|id=13586}}</ref>\n|-\n!National team!!Year!!Apps!!Goals\n|-\n|rowspan=\"3\"|[[Scotland national football team|Scotland]]\n|1972||2||1\n|-\n|1975||1||1\n|-\n|1978||1||0\n|-\n!colspan=\"2\"|